1. Object description

_Hours of the Night_ is an electronic literature, or to be more specific, a powerpoint poem co-authored by M.D Coverley and Stephanie Strickland 10 years ago in 2016. It is both included in Electronic Literature Directory (ELD) and the NEXT.

Coverley states herself that _Hours of the Night_ is an experimental poem that addresses subjects often avoided, such as age and aging, sleep and the night. In collaboration with Strickland, _Hours of the Night_ is a kinetic poetry presented in multiple digital formats, including Powerpoint Slideshow, a standalone Powerpoint file, and an MP4 video. It is compatible with laptop, tablet and smartphone interface. Specifically, the slideshow opens directly in presentation mode after it is downloaded. The full functionality is dependent on the operating system and font availability.

The website that holds the project is live.
The address is as follows:
https://hoursofthenight.com

The text of the work consists of a sequence of animated textual slides, each associated with a specific hour of the night, progressing from evening (18:00) to dawn (6:00). Reading occurs through timed visual presentation, accompanied by curated images and sounds.

2. Textual model and medium

_Hours of the Night_ is linear. A night has a duration of 12 hours. The description of the experience at night is being told in a chronological order from 18:00 to 6:00, with each slide representing an individual hour of time. 

As a Powerpoint poem, the timing of each line and the choice of each image and sound all contribute to the rhythm and structure of the poem. Those elements are predefined by authors and the meaning making of each line of poem is dependent on the temporal progression, not by the decision of the audience. There are no hyperlink, branching paths or navigational choice. Therefore, _Hours of the Night_ is of no interactivity, modularity or generativity. 

Its creativity and readability relies highly on its multimedia attribute. The PowerPoint slideshow interface enforces its smooth and automatic progression. Just as Coverly has stated herself: "We worked very hard to find the right palette, the right (freely available) images, the sounds and their timing. "(Coverley, 2017) These carefully selected images of trees, night sky with meteor, epitaph of Yeats, alongside with the quote from T.S.Eliot and the sound of the foghorn at the cover slide, all contribute to the tranquility of the night, the awareness of the passage of time, whence we meditate and stargaze. 

3. Narratology

_Hours of Night_ adopts temporal progression, but it is not narrative and the scheme of narratology does not fit. There is no story being told and no characters acting on stage.

This kinetic poetry fits best to the category of descriptive text, 
as it describes the experience at night, both physically and psychologically, in an aesthetical way, without telling a specific story about it.

The quantitative analysis of _Hours of the Night_ is feasible as readers are able to download and extract the full text from the Powerpoint fie.

From the result generated by Voyant tool, it is found that the most frequent words of the kinetic poetry are _00_, which stands for the time on the left right corner of the slide, and _"sleep"_, _"night"_, _"hours"_, _"waking"_, _"undone"_, _"stairs"_, _"light"_, _"dawn"_. 
It is also observed from the terms tool that there're many words marked with red color which express negative or pessimistic emotions, such as _"undone"_, _"tense"_, _"sink"_, _"revert"_, _"hard"_, _"erase"_, _"death"_, _"cold"_, _"break"_. There's no work marked in green color expect _"dawn"_ which marks the end of the long night and which is the end of the story. 
To go up and down the _"stairs"_ shows the restlessness of night. _"Tense"_, _"hard_ to sleep", still _"undone"_ shows the experience of insomnia. These words testify that the authors dwell in the subjects of aging, passing of time in this quiet nighttime meditation. But the poem ends with the epitaph of Yeats that instructs passersby to view life and death with detached, stoic objectivity with _"cold"_ eye on life and _"death"_, which is also a reminder for authors themselves. 

5. Reflection

What this object makes possible (affordances)?

This imagery of starry night is vivid and the transition of time from dusk till dawn is more immersive with the help of curated images and sounds. 

What it makes difficult (limits)?

The reading pace differs from person to person, while the timing of each slide is preset. Some people may find it fast, whereas some may find it slow.
The functionality of this kinetic poetry could not benefit people of visual/vision impairment. 

What would be lost if treated like a print text?

The kinetic poetry becomes static and loses its multimedia attribute. The rhyme and structure solely depends on the permutations and combinations of the only form of text.
